menu "breadboard: bb_sink_udp"

config BB_SINK_UDP_ENABLE
    bool "Enable UDP telemetry egress sink"
    default n
    help
        Compiles in bb_sink_udp, an additive fan-out bb_pub sink that emits
        one bb_udp_frame datagram (kind=TELEMETRY) per publish over IPv4 UDP.
        Coexists with bb_sink_mqtt / bb_sink_http — not the bb_pub
        exclusive-sink arbiter.

        This is a menu-gate for the sibling options below (_MTU,
        _AUTOREGISTER) — it controls their visibility and defaults in
        menuconfig only. Like other tier-2 satellites, the bb_sink_udp
        component sources compile whenever the component is added to a
        consumer's REQUIRES, regardless of this flag; actual runtime
        behavior (whether the sink ever sends a datagram) is gated by
        _AUTOREGISTER or by the consumer's own manual
        bb_sink_udp_init()/bb_sink_udp()/bb_pub_add_sink() call sequence.

        Destination config (host/port/broadcast) is no longer configured
        here — it moved to the bb_udp_client transport component (see
        components/bb_udp_client/Kconfig, CONFIG_BB_UDP_PORT /
        CONFIG_BB_UDP_BROADCAST) per KB#702/#710.

config BB_SINK_UDP_MTU
    int "Max encoded datagram size (bytes)"
    default 1400
    range 512 2048
    depends on BB_SINK_UDP_ENABLE
    help
        Upper bound on the encoded bb_udp_frame (header + topic + payload).
        A publish whose encoded frame exceeds this is dropped (never
        fragmented) and counted by bb_sink_udp_dropped().

        This buffer is a plain stack allocation (uint8_t buf[MTU]) inside
        udp_publish(), which runs on the bb_pub worker task — its stack must
        be sized to cover this allocation plus its own call-frame overhead;
        see CONFIG_BB_PUB_WORKER_STACK.

        Floor is 512, not the 11-byte frame-header minimum: a realistic
        fully-qualified topic ("metrics/<hostname>/<subtopic>") plus a
        small JSON payload routinely runs 100-300+ bytes, and 256 was found
        too tight to leave headroom for that in practice. Ceiling is 2048
        to stay under the common Ethernet/WiFi path MTU (1500) with room
        for IP/UDP headers, while still allowing jumbo-frame LANs some
        margin; values above 2048 risk IP fragmentation, which this sink
        deliberately never performs (oversized frames are dropped instead).

endmenu
